{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A Lua script for warping and stretching the positions of MIDI CCs and notes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script only affects events in the MIDI editor lane under the mouse cursor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Useful for changing a linear CC ramp into more complex logistic-type curves.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Useful for accelerating and decelerating a series of evenly spaced notes, as is typical in a trill.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Select MIDI events to be warped (the script works on any CCs, notes, text or sysex events).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Position mouse in lane, {\i within} the time range of the selected events. (Events to left and right of mouse position will be stretch separately.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab Press the shortcut key. (Do not press any mouse button.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab Move mouse left or right to stretch the corresponding side, or move mouse up or down to warp towards or away from mouse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5)\tx360\tab To stop the script, move the mouse out of the CC lane, or press the shortcut key again.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two ways in which this script can be run:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab First, the script can be linked to its own easy-to-remember shortcut key, such as "2". (Using the standard steps of linking any REAPER action to a shortcut key.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Second, this script, together with other "js_" scripts that edit the "lane under mouse", can each be linked to a toolbar button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab In this case, each script need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "js_Run the js_'lane under mouse' script that is selected in toolbar.lua" script needs to be linked to a keyboard shortcut (as well as a mousewheel shortcut).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Clicking the toolbar button will 'arm' the linked script (and the button will light up), and this selected (armed) script can then be run by using the shortcut for the aforementioned "js_Run..." script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab For further instructions - please refer to the "js_Run..." script.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since this function is a user script, the way it responds to shortcut keys and mouse buttons is opposite to that of REAPER's built-in mouse actions with mouse modifiers: To run the script, press the shortcut key {\i once} to start the script and then move the mouse or mousewheel {\i without} pressing any mouse buttons. Press the shortcut key again once to stop the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (The first time that the script is stopped, REAPER will pop up a dialog box asking whether to terminate or restart the script. Select "Terminate" and "Remember my answer for this script".)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIP: The responsiveness of the MIDI editor is significantly influenced by the total number of events in the visible and editable takes. If the MIDI editor is slow, try reducing the number of editable and visible tracks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIP 2: If the MIDI editor gets slow and jerky when a certain VST plugin is loaded, check for graphics driver incompatibility by disabling graphics acceleration in the plugin.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Arch selected CCs or velocities in lane under mouse towards mouse position, using a linear or power curve. (The shape of the curve can be changed with the mousewheel.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Useful for when you want to tweak an existing, complex CC or velocity curve up or down, so that you do not need to re-draw the curve.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Useful for quickly applying and auditioning crescendo-decrescendo (fade-in and fade-out) curves.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab Select events to be arched (such as a CC or velocity curve).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Position mouse in lane.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab Press shortcut key.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 4)\tx360\tab The event closest to the left of the mouse position will be raised or lowered to the mouse vertical position.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 5)\tx360\tab The mousewheel controls the shape of the curve (from linear to parabolic and other power curves).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 6)\tx360\tab To stop the script, press the shortcut key again, or move the mouse out of the CC lane.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The user can customize the speed and resolution of arching by changing the "archResolution" variable in the USER AREA of the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script therefore requires:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab a keyboard shortcut to start the script, as well as\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab a mousewheel modifier to control the shape of the Arching curve.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 KEYBOARD SHORTCUT\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two ways in which the script can be started via a keyboard shortcut:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab First, the script can be linked to its own easy-to-remember shortcut key, such as "A".\line (Using the standard steps of linking any REAPER action to a shortcut key.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Second, this script, together with other "js_" scripts that edit the "lane under mouse", can each be linked to a toolbar button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab In this case, each script does not need to be linked to its own shortcut key.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Instead, only the master control script, with the long name "js_Run the js_'lane under mouse' script that is selected in toolbar.lua" needs to be linked to a keyboard shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Clicking the toolbar button will 'arm' the linked script (and the button will light up), and this selected (armed) script can then be run by using the shortcut for the aforementioned "js_Run..." script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab For further instructions - please refer to the "js_Run..." script.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Note: Since this function is a user script, the way it responds to shortcut keys and mouse buttons is opposite to that of REAPER's built-in mouse actions with mouse modifiers: To run the script, press the shortcut key {\i once} to start the script and then move the mouse {\i without} pressing any mouse buttons. Press the shortcut key again once to stop the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (The first time that the script is stopped, REAPER will pop up a dialog box asking whether to terminate or restart the script. Select "Terminate" and "Remember my answer for this script".)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSEWHEEL MODIFIER\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A mousewheel modifier is a combination such as Ctrl+mousewheel, that can be assigned to an Action, similar to how keyboard shortcuts are assigned.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As is the case with keyboard shortcuts, the script can either be controlled via its own mousewheel modifier, or via the mousewheel modifier that is linked to the "js_Run..." control script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Linking each script to its own mousewheel modifier is not ideal, since it would mean that the user must remember several modifier combinations, one for each script. (Mousewheel modifiers such as Ctrl+Shift+mousewheel are more difficult to remember than keyboard shortcuts such as "A".)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An easier option is to link a single mousewheel+modifier shortcut to the "js_Run..." script, and this single mousewheel+modifier can then be used to control any of the other "lane under mouse" scripts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 NOTE: The mousewheel modifier that is assigned to the "js_Run..." script can be used to control the other scripts, including the Arching scripts, even if these scripts were started from their own keyboard shortcuts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIPS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The responsiveness of the MIDI editor is significantly influenced by the total number of events in the visible and editable takes. If the MIDI editor is slow, try reducing the number of editable and visible tracks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If the MIDI editor gets slow and jerky when a certain VST plugin is loaded, check for graphics driver incompatibility by disabling graphics acceleration in the plugin.\sa180\par}
}

