{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Draw linear or curved ramps of CC and pitchwheel events in real time (chasing start values).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An improvement over REAPER's built-in "Linear ramp CC events" mouse action:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If snap to grid is enabled in the MIDI editor, the endpoints of the ramp will snap to grid, allowing precise positioning of the ramp (allowing, for example, the insertion of a pitch riser at the exact position of a note).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab By using the mousewheel, the shape of the ramp can be changed from linear to curved (allowing the easy insertion of parablic shapes).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script can optionally chase existing CC values, instead of starting at the mouse's vertical position. This ensures that CC values change smoothly.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script inserts new CCs, instead of only editing existing CCs. (CCs are inserted at the density set in Preferences -> MIDI editor -> "Events per quarter note when drawing in CC lanes".)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script does not change or delete existing events until execution ends, so there are no 'overshoot remnants' if the mouse movement overshoots the target endpoint.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The events in the newly inserted ramp are automatically selected and other events in the same lane are deselected, which allows immediate further shaping of the ramp (using, for example, the warping or arching scripts).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script can optionally skip redundant CCs (that is, CCs with the same value as the preceding CC).\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 INSTRUCTIONS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script requires:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab a keyboard shortcut to start the script, as well as\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab a mousewheel modifier to control the shape of the ramp.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 KEYBOARD SHORTCUT\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two ways in which the script can be started via a keyboard shortcut:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab First, the script can be linked to its own easy-to-remember shortcut key, such as "Ctrl+tab" for chase+ramp.\line (Using the standard steps of linking any REAPER action to a shortcut key.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Second, this script, together with other "js_" scripts that edit the "lane under mouse", can each be linked to a toolbar button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab In this case, each script does not need to be linked to its own shortcut key.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Instead, only the master control script, with the long name "js_Run the js_'lane under mouse' script that is selected in toolbar.lua" needs to be linked to a keyboard shortcut.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Clicking the toolbar button will 'arm' the linked script (and the button will light up), and this selected (armed) script can then be run by using the shortcut for the aforementioned "js_Run..." script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab For further instructions - please refer to the "js_Run..." script.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Note: Since this function is a user script, the way it responds to shortcut keys and mouse buttons is opposite to that of REAPER's built-in mouse actions with mouse modifiers: To run the script, press the shortcut key {\i once} to start the script and then move the mouse {\i without} pressing any mouse buttons. Press the shortcut key again once to stop the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (The first time that the script is stopped, REAPER will pop up a dialog box asking whether to terminate or restart the script. Select "Terminate" and "Remember my answer for this script".)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 MOUSEWHEEL MODIFIER\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A mousewheel modifier is a combination such as Ctrl+mousewheel, that can be assigned to an Action, similar to how keyboard shortcuts are assigned.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 As is the case with keyboard shortcuts, the script can either be controlled via its own mousewheel modifier, or via the mousewheel modifier that is linked to the "js_Run..." control script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Linking each script to its own mousewheel modifier is not ideal, since it would mean that the user must remember several modifier combinations, one for each script. (Mousewheel modifiers such as Ctrl+Shift+mousewheel are more difficult to remember than keyboard shortcuts such as "tab".)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An easier option is to link a single mousewheel+modifier shortcut to the "js_Run..." script, and this single mousewheel+modifier can then be used to control any of the other "lane under mouse" scripts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 NOTE: The mousewheel modifier that is assigned to the "js_Run..." script can be used to control the other scripts, including the Draw ramps scripts, even if these scripts were started from their own keyboard shortcuts.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 USER CUSTOMIZABLE PARAMETERS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To enable/disable chasing of existing CC values, set the "doChase" parameter in the USER AREA at the beginning of the script to "false".\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To disable snap-to-grid altogether, irrespective of the MIDI editor's snap setting, set "neverSnapToGrid" to "true".\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The default ramp shape can be changed from linear to any power curve, by changing the "defaultShapePower" parameter. To set the default shape to parabolic, use 2 or 0.5.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To enable/disable skipping of redundant CCs, set the "skipRedundant" parameter.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To enable/disable deselection of other CCs in the same lane as the new ramp (and in the active take), set the "deselectEverythingInLane" parameter. This allows easy editing of only the new ramp after drawing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 PERFORMANCE TIPS\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The responsiveness of the MIDI editor is significantly influenced by the total number of events in the visible and editable takes. If the MIDI editor is slow, try reducing the number of editable and visible tracks.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If the MIDI editor gets slow and jerky when a certain VST plugin is loaded, check for graphics driver incompatibility by disabling graphics acceleration in the plugin.\sa180\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 DESCRIPTION\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Draw linear or curved ramps of CC and pitchwheel events in real time (without chasing start values).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 An improvement over REAPER's built-in "Linear ramp CC events" mouse action:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab If snap to grid is enabled in the MIDI editor, the endpoints of the ramp will snap to grid, allowing precise positioning of the ramp (allowing, for example, the insertion of a pitch riser at the exact position of a note).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab By using the mousewheel, the shape of the ramp can be changed from linear to curved (allowing the easy insertion of parablic shapes).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script can optionally chase existing CC values, instead of starting at the mouse's vertical position. This ensures that CC values change smoothly.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script inserts new CCs, instead of only editing existing CCs. (CCs are inserted at the density set in Preferences -> MIDI editor -> "Events per quarter note when drawing in CC lanes".)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script does not change or delete existing events until execution ends, so there are no 'overshoot remnants' if the mouse movement overshoots the target endpoint.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The events in the newly inserted ramp are automatically selected and other events in the same lane are deselected, which allows immediate further shaping of the ramp (using, for example, the warping or arching scripts).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The script can optionally skip redundant CCs (that is, CCs with the same value as the preceding CC).\sa180\par}
