\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script helps to improve the UI by allowing js_ MIDI editing functions to be selected via toolbar buttons, similar to FL Studio and other DAWs.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Any js_ script that edits the 'lane under mouse' and that has been linked to a toolbar button can be run using a single keyboard shortcut that has been linked to this script -- therefore no more need to remember a different shortcut for each script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script currently works with the following js_ MIDI editing scripts:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \f1  ~ Stretch \line
 ~ Tilt\line
 ~ Compress or expand\line
 ~ 1-sided warp (accelerate)\line
 ~ 2-sided warp (and stretch)\line
 ~ Draw linear or curved ramp in real time\line
 ~ Draw linear or curved ramp in real time (chasing start values)\line
 ~ Draw sine curve in real time\line
 ~ Draw sine curve in real time (chasing start values)\line
 ~ Split notes\line
 ~ Split selected notes\line
 ~ Remove redundancies (in lane under mouse)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Any user-customized variants of these scripts can also be added to the toolbar.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Notes\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The scripts listed above are those that work with events in the lane under mouse.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Since the mouse needs to be positioned over the MIDI editor's CC lanes or notes area for these scripts to work, they cannot be run directly from toolbar buttons.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Scripts that work with events in the last-clicked lane (such as variants the LFO Tool or the Remove Redundancies script) can be run directly from the toolbar.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script must be linked to a keyboard shortcut (such as "S") as well as a mousewheel shortcut (such as Ctrl+mousewheel).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script should not be linked to a toolbar button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The js_ MIDI functions listed above should each be linked to a toolbar button. (They can also be linked to their own keyboard shortcuts, but this is not necessary.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To run the selected js_ MIDI function:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab click its button, which will light up,\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab move the mouse to its position in the CC lane or notes area, and\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 3)\tx360\tab press the shortcut key for this "Run the js_..." script.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Note: Since this script is a user script, the way it responds to shortcut keys and mouse buttons is opposite to that of REAPER's built-in mouse actions with mouse modifiers: To run the script, press the shortcut key {\i once} to start the script and then move the mouse {\i without} pressing any mouse buttons. Press the shortcut key again once to stop the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (The first time that the script is stopped, REAPER will pop up a dialog box asking whether to terminate or restart the script. Select "Terminate" and "Remember my answer for this script".)\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script selects and deselects notes, based on a pattern that the user can draw in a GUI.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 For example, the pattern can be drawn to select notes 1, 3 and 4 in a six-step pattern.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The length of the pattern as well as the steps that will be selected are determined by the user. (The maximum pattern length is 99 steps.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script offers two modes: "Step pattern" and "Measure division", which can be toggled by clicking on the "Mode" text in the GUI. In "Measure division" mode, notes are selected and deselected based on their beat positions in the measure.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In Step pattern mode, notes that start within one grid length of each other are regarded as one unit (e.g. chord or glissando), and will be selected/deselected together.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 First, select the note on which the step pattern must be applied. (Of course, some of these notes will later be deselected by the script.)\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Then, run the script and draw the desired pattern - the note selection will be updated in real time.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When you need to work with a new set of notes, simply click the "Load new set of notes" text.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If no notes are selected when the script is started, the script will dim out the step pattern display, and wait for the user to load a new set of notes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To draw patterns that are longer than the initial size of the GUI, simply widen the GUI.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To toggle between the two modes, "Step pattern" and "Measure division", simply click the "Mode" text at the top of the GUI.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 NEW IN VERSION 1.20:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The user can freely edit CCs or velocities in the MIDI editor while a set of notes is loaded, without having to reload the notes after editing.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If the pitches or positions of the loaded {\i notes} are edited in the MIDI editor, it may confuse the script, but the script will try to add any {\i selected} and edited notes to the set of loaded, active notes.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Therefore, if you change the pitch of some of the loaded notes, simply ensure that these notes are still selected when clicking in the GUI again, and these edited notes will remain loaded.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 TIP:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script works well with the "js_Deselect all notes outside time selection (from all takes).lua" script. Use the piano roll keys to select all notes in a range of pitches, and then run the Deselect script to limit the note selection to the time selection.\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Split (slice) multiple notes by drawing a "cutting line" with the mouse in the MIDI editor or inline piano roll.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Notes that intersect the cutting line will be split at the position of intersection.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 If snap-to-grid is enabled, the notes will be split at the grid.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 To use, position mouse in the 'notes' area of the piano roll, press the shortcut key once, and then move the mouse to draw the cutting line.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 There are two ways in which this script can be run:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 1)\tx360\tab First, the script can be linked to its own shortcut key.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li360 \fi-360 2)\tx360\tab Second, this script, together with other "js_" scripts that edit the "lane under mouse", can each be linked to a toolbar button.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab In this case, each script need not be linked to its own shortcut key. Instead, only the accompanying "js_Run the js_'lane under mouse' script that is selected in toolbar.lua" script needs to be linked to a keyboard shortcut (as well as a mousewheel shortcut).\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab Clicking the toolbar button will 'arm' the linked script (and the button will light up), and this selected (armed) script can then be run by using the shortcut for the aforementioned "js_Run..." script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li720 \fi-360 \endash \tx360\tab For further instructions - please refer to the "js_Run..." script.\sa180\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the script's USER AREA (near the beginning of the script), the user can customize:\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab The thickness of the cutting line\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab Whether all notes or only selected notes should be split.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Note: Since this function is a user script, the way it responds to shortcut keys and mouse buttons is opposite to that of REAPER's built-in mouse actions with mouse modifiers: To run the script, press the shortcut key {\i once} to start the script and then move the mouse {\i without} pressing any mouse buttons. Press the shortcut key again once to stop the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 (The first time that the script is stopped, REAPER will pop up a dialog box asking whether to terminate or restart the script. Select "Terminate" and "Remember my answer for this script".)\par}
}

