{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 A Lua script for viewing and editing the tempo map in the MIDI editor.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The tempo map is displayed in a CC lane, and any edits in the CC lane are mirrored in the tempo map.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Create a track names "Tempo" and insert a single MIDI take in the track.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab (The take should cover the time span of the tempo map that will be viewed/edited.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Optionally, rename the CC lane to "Tempo" or any other suitable name.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab (The actions and menu items to rename CC lanes are somewhat misleadingly named, and only refer to "Note names". In the MIDI editor, make the Tempo track active, then go to File -> Note names -> Load note names from file. The file only needs to contain a single line, such as "CC31 Tempo".)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The default CC lane is the 14-bit 31/63 lane, but alternative lanes can be selected by the user in the script's user area.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Run the script.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab (The script can be linked to a toolbar button, which will indicate the activation status of the script.)\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Once the script is running, if any changes are made directly to the Master track's tempo envelope, (within the take's time span), the script will deactivate.\line When the script is re-activated, the new changes can be re-copied into the Tempo track.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Note: This script is not compatible with linear tempo changes. However, this is not a grave disadvantage, since\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab linear tempo changes are somewhat buggy in current versions of REAPER ~v5.35, and\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa0 \li360 \fi-360 \bullet \tx360\tab SWS's tempo map actions also require square tempo changes.\sa180\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The first time that the script is stopped, REAPER will pop up a dialog box asking whether to terminate or restart the script. Select "Terminate" and "Remember my answer for this script".)\par}
}

{\rtf1\ansi\deff0{\fonttbl{\f0 \fswiss Helvetica;}{\f1 Courier;}}
{\colortbl;\red255\green0\blue0;\red0\green0\blue255;}
\widowctrl\hyphauto

{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Description\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When the MIDI editor's active take is switched via the track list to a take that is out of view, the MIDI editor will automatically "Zoom to content". If the newly active MIDI take is very large, "Zoom to content" provides a nice overview of the entire item, so that the user can easily locate the relevant MIDI data. However, zooming in again can be a hassle.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This script is therefore intended to provide an easy, one-click action to zoom in, without requiring the user to change the note, time or loop selection.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Instructions\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Simply point the mouse to the appropriate position in the MIDI item and press the linked shortcut or mouse modifier.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 In the script's USER AREA, the user can change the number of measures that the script zooms to, and these modified scripts can be saved under different names and linked to different shortcuts or mouse modifiers.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \b \fs36 Warning\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The script temporarily changes the loop region, so it may be safer to avoid running the script during playback or recording.\par}
}

